The paper discusses millimeter-wave propagation measurements and path loss models for 5G systems, which are relevant to several sub-categories in computer science. The most likely category is cs.IT (Information Theory), as the paper focuses on the analysis of path loss models and their accuracy in estimating large-scale propagation in wireless communication systems. The second likely category is cs.NI (Networking and Internet Architecture), as the paper discusses the propagation of signals in urban micro-cellular and indoor office scenarios, which are relevant to wireless networking. The third likely category is cs.MM (Multimedia), as the paper discusses the use of millimeter-wave frequencies for 5G systems, which are relevant to multimedia applications that require high bandwidth and low latency. The fourth likely category is cs.MA (Multi-Agent Systems), as the paper discusses the use of path loss models for modeling the behavior of wireless communication systems, which can be viewed as a multi-agent system. The fifth likely category is cs.SY (Systems and Control), as the paper discusses the use of path loss models for controlling the behavior of wireless communication systems.
